{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567672"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:05:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:05:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19228"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19228","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19228"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.67,0.23,0.02,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11962"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90793"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11962","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11962"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19228"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74883"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"928"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"3029"},{"type":"tags","id":"4951"},{"type":"tags","id":"4986"},{"type":"tags","id":"4989"},{"type":"tags","id":"4990"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"5351"},{"type":"tags","id":"6146"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11645"},{"type":"tags","id":"11648"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11811"},{"type":"tags","id":"12734"},{"type":"tags","id":"12852"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"28065"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28068"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32902"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45043"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90793","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90793"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old Aboriginal woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a sprained ankle. During the consultation, she appears quiet and makes minimal eye contact. She has attended the practice several times over the past year with various minor injuries. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She works as a retail assistant and lives with her partner and two children. On examination, she appears reserved. Her vital signs are within normal limits. There is mild swelling and tenderness of her left lateral ankle.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial approach to this consultation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Complete the ankle examination and provide standard management advice","Ask if she would like an Aboriginal Health Worker to join the consultation","Inquire about her home situation and relationship with her partner","Schedule a follow-up Aboriginal Health Assessment","Provide information about local community support services"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario presents a situation where there are subtle indicators that may suggest underlying issues requiring a culturally safe and sensitive approach. The key is to recognise the importance of cultural considerations in providing appropriate healthcare to Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAsking if she would like a female Aboriginal Health Worker\u003C/strong\u003E to join the consultation is the most appropriate first step. This approach acknowledges the importance of cultural safety and respects the patient\u0027s autonomy by seeking her permission. It provides the patient with a culturally appropriate support person who can help bridge any cultural and communication gaps. Aboriginal Health Workers can help establish trust and create a more comfortable environment for sensitive discussions about health and wellbeing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompleting the ankle examination and providing standard management advice\u003C/strong\u003E would address the presenting complaint but misses an opportunity to establish a deeper therapeutic relationship. This approach could be seen as dismissive of potential underlying issues affecting the patient\u0027s wellbeing and fails to provide holistic care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirectly inquiring about her home situation\u003C/strong\u003E without first establishing appropriate cultural safety and trust could be confronting and may cause the patient to disengage from healthcare services. While exploring social determinants of health is important, the approach must be culturally appropriate and properly timed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScheduling a follow-up appointment for a comprehensive health assessment\u003C/strong\u003E has merit but doesn\u0027t address the immediate need to establish cultural safety and trust. Without first creating a safe environment in the current consultation, the patient may not return for the follow-up appointment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProviding information about local community support services\u003C/strong\u003E without first understanding the patient\u0027s specific needs and establishing trust could be perceived as presumptuous and may not address her actual concerns. This approach might also overwhelm the patient with information before a therapeutic relationship has been established.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECultural safety in healthcare involves understanding and respecting Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples\u0027 cultural identity, family connections, and community relationships. It requires healthcare providers to acknowledge the impact of historical trauma and work within culturally appropriate frameworks to provide effective care. Building trust is essential before exploring sensitive topics, and having culturally appropriate support people present can facilitate more effective communication and care.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cultural safety is essential when discussing sensitive topics with Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander patients.","Building trust and rapport through culturally appropriate communication is crucial for effective healthcare delivery.","Understanding the role of family, community, and cultural obligations is vital in healthcare discussions with Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander patients.","Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander health workers and practitioners provide a culturally safe workforce with skills to support patients experiencing family violence and strengthen relationships between Indigenous patients and non-Indigenous service providers."],"references":["Royal Australian College of General Practitioners . Specific populations: Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander communities . In: White Book. RACGP; 2022. Accessed January 29, 2025. https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/abuse-and-violence/specific-populations/aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-communities"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74883"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19228"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74883","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74883"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T16:05:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T16:07:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11962"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90793"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\